The justice system is already feeling the effects of Covid-19. All prison visits have been banned for 30-days but courts are still an issue. Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - Chief Justice, Mogoeng Mogoeng says all courts and detention facilities will be sanitised to contain the spread of the coronavirus. READ: Coronavirus: Bheki Cele warns against fake news The justice system's containment plans also include a screening of all staff and members of the public. All prison visits have been banned for 30-days but courts remain open. Mogoeng Mogoeng also added that nothing is impossible with prayer. He's called on all religious people to pray together as a country on Wednesday's and Sunday's in groups of no more than 70. SUMMARY: Ramaphosa announces COVID-19 controls President Cyril Ramaphosa declared the coronavirus pandemic a national disaster. At least 62 people have tested positive for COVID-19 and more tests are currently underway. The president says the country is now dealing with the internal transmission of the virus. SUMMARY: Ramaphosa announces COVID-19 controls Watch Chief Justice, Mogoeng Mogoeng's response to coronavirus fears in the video above.  - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp.